{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17460"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10150"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56345"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23823"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher follows 1,000 healthy adults for five years to study the development of type 2 diabetes. During this period, 50 participants develop the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the five-year incidence proportion of type 2 diabetes in this population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.01 or 1% at study end","0.01 or 1% per year","0.95 or 95% disease-free rate","50 cases per 1,000 person-years","0.05 or 5%"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-year incidence proportion is 0.05 or 5%\u003C/strong\u003E, calculated by dividing the number of new cases (50) by the initial population at risk (1,000). This represents the probability of developing type 2 diabetes during the five-year period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.01 or 1% at study end\u003C/strong\u003E: this calculation is incorrect and does not represent a meaningful measure of disease occurrence over the study period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.01 or 1% per year\u003C/strong\u003E: this incorrectly assumes the risk is distributed equally across all five years of the study period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.95 or 95% disease-free rate\u003C/strong\u003E: while this represents the proportion who remained disease-free, it is not the incidence proportion which measures disease occurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50 cases per 1,000 person-years\u003C/strong\u003E: this represents incidence rate, which is a different measure that accounts for varying follow-up times.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncidence proportion is a key measure in epidemiology that provides the probability or risk of developing a condition during a specified time period. It must always be accompanied by the time period to be meaningful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidence proportion (cumulative incidence) measures the probability of developing a condition during a specified time period.","Incidence proportion is calculated by dividing new cases by the population at risk at the start of the period.","Incidence proportion is expressed as a decimal or percentage and must be accompanied by the time period."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001","Peacock, Janet L., and Phil J. Peacock, Oxford Handbook of Medical Statistics 2e, 2 edn, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2020; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2020), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780198743583.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56345"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56345"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:54:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:54:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10150"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70878"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifyi